d operation of five types of "gendered Russian imaginaries" that were explicitly used to bolster support for and legitimize U.S. geopolitical unilateralism after the dissolution of the Soviet Union, demonstrating the ways that the masculinization of U.S. military, political, and financial power after 1991 paved the way for the invasion of Iraq in 2003.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aFeminist theory. 0aMass media and international relations. 0aMass media and nationalism -- United States. 0aMass media and nationalismzUnited States. 0aNational characteristics in mass media. 0aNational characteristics, Russian. 0aNationalism -- United States. 0aNationalism and feminism. 0aNationalismzUnited States. 0aSex role. 4aGender and Sexuality : Gender Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aHistory : History. 4aPolitics and Law : International Relations. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438439778423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438439778/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles